1
00:02:16,236 --> 00:02:18,500
- Did you bring my band of Indians?
- Indians?

2
00:02:18,605 --> 00:02:22,132
Yes, American Indians,
musicians to play in my café.

3
00:02:22,242 --> 00:02:24,972
- Oh, you mean Indians with feathers?
- Yes, with noses.

4
00:02:25,078 --> 00:02:27,376
- Like on the American five cents?
- Yes, yes.

5
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:30,005
- Have you got them on board, yes?
- No.

6
00:02:31,217 --> 00:02:32,775
Thank you, <i>monsieur.</i>

7
00:02:37,690 --> 00:02:41,649
Indians? Indians?
Are you the Wabash Indians Band?

8
00:02:41,728 --> 00:02:42,820
Are you Voyda?

9
00:02:42,896 --> 00:02:45,558
I am Alexander Petrovitch
Moskovich Voyda.

10
00:02:46,132 --> 00:02:47,531
Let's pick it up from there.

11
00:02:47,634 --> 00:02:49,795
We're the boys you hired
to play at your café.

12
00:02:49,869 --> 00:02:52,804
- The Wabash Indianians.
- Indianians?

13
00:02:53,873 --> 00:02:55,738
Is this the same as Indians?

14
00:02:58,211 --> 00:02:59,735
Well, yes, in a sense.

15
00:02:59,846 --> 00:03:03,304
You see, we don't wear our feathers
in warm weather, do we, boys?

16
00:03:03,383 --> 00:03:04,816
- No.
- No, never, never.

17
00:03:04,884 --> 00:03:08,081
- Well, when do we start, Mr. Voyda?
- You don't start.

18
00:03:08,221 --> 00:03:10,655
I cable for Indians and I want Indians!

19
00:03:10,823 --> 00:03:14,759
No pale American face
is going to make me a fool of myself.

20
00:03:14,861 --> 00:03:17,989
Did you ever heard of Alexander
Petrovitch Moskovich Voyda?

21
00:03:18,064 --> 00:03:20,259
- Sure.
- Yes, and how, and how.

22
00:03:20,333 --> 00:03:23,325
As a matter of fact, we hear you're one
of the cleverest fellows in Paris.

23
00:03:23,403 --> 00:03:25,564
In Paris and all Europe.
The whole world.

24
00:03:25,672 --> 00:03:28,368
Well, I was coming to that.
I just wanted to prepare you, that's all.

25
00:03:28,441 --> 00:03:30,204
You got a great bet
in these boys, Mr. Voyda.

26
00:03:30,276 --> 00:03:33,768
- They'll be a knockout in your café.
- They shall never see my café.

27
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:37,077
I ordered Indians, and what do I get?

28
00:03:42,222 --> 00:03:43,655
Wait, Mr. Voyda.

29
00:03:45,425 --> 00:03:46,790
Huck, do the organ number, quick.

30
00:03:46,893 --> 00:03:49,225
Come on, boys, give us the organ number.
Get the gloves out.

31
00:03:49,295 --> 00:03:50,557
- Oh, Mr. Voyda.
- What?

32
00:03:50,630 --> 00:03:51,927
Aren't you going to
give these boys a chance?

33
00:03:51,998 --> 00:03:53,363
No, why should I?

34
00:03:54,133 --> 00:03:56,431
Sorry, Mr. Voyda,
but I'm afraid you've got to listen.

35
00:03:56,536 --> 00:03:58,902
Just submit quietly
and we'll both keep out of jail.

36
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:34,497
Well, how did you like that, Mr. Voyda?
You see, you almost made a mistake.

37
00:05:34,567 --> 00:05:37,001
I made a mistake? You made a mistake.

38
00:05:37,070 --> 00:05:38,628
You are not Indians!

39
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:43,174
The cable mentioned a short engagement.

40
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:45,705
Well, it was a nice trip over.

41
00:05:45,778 --> 00:05:49,009
It'll be a nicer trip going back,
stoking coals.

42
00:05:54,354 --> 00:05:56,549
Come on, boys, the train for Paris.

43
00:06:05,798 --> 00:06:08,062
A grand total of $13.78.

44
00:06:08,901 --> 00:06:10,129
And a button.

45
00:06:11,537 --> 00:06:15,268
Well, boys, at the rate we live,
that'll last us about two months.

46
00:06:15,975 --> 00:06:18,443
Mother told me
there would be days like this.

47
00:06:18,544 --> 00:06:20,876
Say, listen,
they dance in Paris, don't they?

48
00:06:20,947 --> 00:06:22,938
All we have to do
is find out who pays the fiddler.

49
00:06:23,049 --> 00:06:24,778
Does anyone know anyone in Paris?

50
00:06:24,884 --> 00:06:27,375
That top sergeant brother of mine
gave me some addresses.

51
00:06:27,453 --> 00:06:28,545
Quiet.

52
00:06:29,288 --> 00:06:33,088
Wait! I know somebody, a little girl
who used to live next door to me.

53
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:36,617
Gee, I was crazy about her, too.
She's a sensation in Paris,

54
00:06:36,729 --> 00:06:39,289
she's a star of some show or something.

55
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:42,934
- She'll help us.
- Well, what's her name?

56
00:06:43,836 --> 00:06:45,269
What was her name?

57
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:49,237
Gee, I could find her like that
if I could only remember her name.

58
00:06:49,308 --> 00:06:51,173
Anybody else you know
you can't remember?

59
00:06:51,277 --> 00:06:53,609
Yeah, but I can't think who they are.

60
00:06:53,679 --> 00:06:58,013
I know, it's Lizzie, Lizzie...
Elizabeth Gatz.

61
00:06:58,117 --> 00:06:59,345
That's it. Elizabeth Gatz.

62
00:06:59,452 --> 00:07:00,919
What a beautiful name.

63
00:07:00,987 --> 00:07:05,253
Whether you find your Lizzie or not,
I've got an aunt in Paris. Aunt Minnie.

64
00:07:05,358 --> 00:07:07,189
Can Aunt Minnie use a band?

65
00:07:07,527 --> 00:07:09,688
Probably not. She's a dressmaker.

66
00:07:10,029 --> 00:07:13,658
Well, I've knitted and tatted
all my life, but I've never sewed.

67
00:07:13,766 --> 00:07:16,564
- She's very rich and famous. She might...
- Why didn't you say so before?

68
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:17,961
She's Roberta.

69
00:07:18,037 --> 00:07:19,163
Roberta?

70
00:07:20,540 --> 00:07:22,269
- This Roberta?
- Yeah.

71
00:07:22,341 --> 00:07:24,707
They tell me in Paris if you
don't buy your gowns from Roberta,

72
00:07:24,777 --> 00:07:26,301
you're not dressed at all.

73
00:07:26,379 --> 00:07:29,041
I see, nude if you don't, and nude if you do.

74
00:07:41,627 --> 00:07:43,151
Grab my bag, will you?

75
00:07:44,831 --> 00:07:48,267
Listen, ask your aunt Minnie if she knows
where we can find Lizzie Gatz, will you?

76
00:07:48,334 --> 00:07:50,495
- Okay. I won't be long.
- All right.

77
00:07:51,237 --> 00:07:54,536
You fellows pick yourselves
some comfortable easy chairs.

78
00:08:43,222 --> 00:08:44,280
Hey!

79
00:08:48,861 --> 00:08:49,953
Hey!

80
00:09:04,911 --> 00:09:08,904
What am I supposed to do here
besides pray? Or can't you speak English?

81
00:09:12,418 --> 00:09:14,318
Well, the old trap won't go.

82
00:09:15,121 --> 00:09:18,056
Oh, what's the use? Just a dumb foreigner.

83
00:09:19,158 --> 00:09:20,750
Oh, here, here, here.

84
00:09:20,993 --> 00:09:23,553
You mustn't do that. You might be killed.

85
00:09:24,263 --> 00:09:27,164
Oh, you speak English.

86
00:09:27,767 --> 00:09:28,825
Ladislaw.

87
00:09:44,684 --> 00:09:47,175
Oh, don't go away. I want to thank you.

88
00:09:47,286 --> 00:09:49,550
Gee, you saved my life.
I'm ever so much obliged to you.

89
00:09:49,655 --> 00:09:51,350
Oh, it's nothing at all.

90
00:09:51,557 --> 00:09:54,720
Oh, I mean you're welcome, of course.

91
00:09:54,827 --> 00:09:56,886
Do you know
where I can find Madam Roberta?

92
00:09:56,996 --> 00:09:58,827
Yes. Come with me.

93
00:10:03,903 --> 00:10:06,804
I didn't really mean that
about a dumb foreigner.

94
00:10:07,073 --> 00:10:08,335
I forgive you.

95
00:10:08,541 --> 00:10:10,008
Gee, that's swell.

96
00:10:10,343 --> 00:10:12,243
You speak English beautifully.

97
00:10:12,345 --> 00:10:14,677
Long ago I went to school in England.

98
00:10:15,848 --> 00:10:16,906
Did you like it?

99
00:10:17,016 --> 00:10:20,884
Oh, yes, I like the English.
And the Americans, too.

100
00:10:21,854 --> 00:10:23,321
Gee, that's swell.

101
00:10:23,656 --> 00:10:25,988
- I'm an American.
- Gee, that's...

102
00:10:27,026 --> 00:10:29,324
I mean, I thought so.

103
00:10:31,163 --> 00:10:32,926
Will you sit here, please?

104
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,092
Thank you.

105
00:10:56,122 --> 00:11:00,286
But Minnie, you've made a mistake
in the year. You don't look a day over...

106
00:11:00,893 --> 00:11:03,225
- Stephanie!
- How do you do, Lord Henry?

107
00:11:03,295 --> 00:11:04,694
My dear.

108
00:11:05,097 --> 00:11:08,260
I saw your cousin,
Prince Peter, last week in Rome.

109
00:11:08,401 --> 00:11:11,029
He asked after you most solicitously.

110
00:11:11,137 --> 00:11:14,231
I hope you told him I had gone to work
and he should do the same.

111
00:11:14,306 --> 00:11:16,866
When all you titled aristocrats get jobs,

112
00:11:16,942 --> 00:11:19,570
maybe Europe can settle down
to a few years' peace.

113
00:11:19,645 --> 00:11:20,942
What is it, Stephanie?

114
00:11:21,047 --> 00:11:24,778
There's a young gentleman outside
from America, waiting to see you.

115
00:11:24,884 --> 00:11:26,818
Young gentleman from America?

116
00:11:27,253 --> 00:11:28,311
John.

117
00:11:28,554 --> 00:11:29,646
John!

118
00:11:29,989 --> 00:11:31,650
Bring him in, Stephanie. Bring him in!

119
00:11:31,757 --> 00:11:34,089
No, wait. Don't let him come
until I've powdered my nose.

120
00:11:34,160 --> 00:11:37,391
Give me that compact, Henry.
Quick, quick, the compact!

121
00:11:37,797 --> 00:11:39,230
How does he look?

122
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:45,231
He must look all right.

123
00:11:46,138 --> 00:11:48,470
- Send him in, Stephanie.
- Yes, <i>madame.</i>

124
00:11:54,346 --> 00:11:57,747
- This "John from America", who is he?
- My nephew.

125
00:11:57,950 --> 00:12:01,511
I met him when I was there a few years
ago and took a great fancy to him.

126
00:12:01,620 --> 00:12:02,985
He's quite famous in his way.

127
00:12:03,089 --> 00:12:06,320
"All-American halfback" or
"three quarters back" or something.

128
00:12:06,425 --> 00:12:08,120
- Really?
- Yes, you know, it's queer,

129
00:12:08,194 --> 00:12:09,752
but when you
happen to like your relatives,

130
00:12:09,829 --> 00:12:11,160
you like them better than other people.

131
00:12:11,263 --> 00:12:13,993
- And if you hate them?
- Don't be obvious, Henry.

132
00:12:14,100 --> 00:12:16,330
He was the only one of the whole tribe

133
00:12:16,435 --> 00:12:19,131
who was polite to me
during my entire visit.

134
00:12:19,371 --> 00:12:20,838
I like him, Henry.

135
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:24,601
He's like a big, affectionate,
blundering Newfoundland dog.

136
00:12:25,111 --> 00:12:26,601
I'd like to see him grow up.

137
00:12:26,679 --> 00:12:29,978
- How big is he now?
- Oh, about 6'2".

138
00:12:33,652 --> 00:12:37,349
John, my dear, I'm so glad to see you.

139
00:12:37,456 --> 00:12:39,651
It's swell to see you, Aunt Minnie.

140
00:12:40,559 --> 00:12:43,960
- Here he is, Henry, here is my...
- Newfoundland dog?

141
00:12:44,697 --> 00:12:46,790
I was telling him about you, John.

142
00:12:46,866 --> 00:12:50,324
This is Lord Henry Delves,
a really grand person.

143
00:12:51,203 --> 00:12:55,230
And this is Stephanie, my able assistant
whom I couldn't do without.

144
00:13:04,183 --> 00:13:07,516
Well, young man, I think your aunt
should be very much complimented.

145
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:09,485
When I was in Paris at your age,

146
00:13:09,555 --> 00:13:12,046
I didn't spend my time visiting my aunts.

147
00:13:12,558 --> 00:13:14,992
Maybe you didn't
have any aunts like Aunt Minnie.

148
00:13:15,060 --> 00:13:16,493
Very prettily said, John.

149
00:13:16,562 --> 00:13:18,962
There aren't any like your aunt Minnie.

150
00:13:19,031 --> 00:13:21,659
Well, goodbye, young man,
I'm off to catch a train,

151
00:13:21,734 --> 00:13:23,565
but in a fortnight I'll be back.

152
00:13:23,669 --> 00:13:26,502
And then, as I understand is the custom
in your country,

153
00:13:26,572 --> 00:13:29,234
we'll go places and do something.

154
00:13:33,512 --> 00:13:36,811
Goodbye, Minnie,
miss me just a little, won't you?

155
00:13:37,049 --> 00:13:38,880
A very great deal, my dear.

156
00:13:46,058 --> 00:13:47,548
Nice old duck, isn't he?

157
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:49,491
Oh, he isn't so terribly old.

158
00:13:49,562 --> 00:13:52,656
Oh, I didn't mean in years, Aunt Minnie.
I meant I like him.

159
00:13:52,731 --> 00:13:53,857
Do you?

160
00:13:54,333 --> 00:13:56,392
Then you're a good judge of men.

161
00:13:56,902 --> 00:14:00,099
Now, tell me about this young lady
you wrote me about. What was her name?

162
00:14:00,206 --> 00:14:02,231
Sophie. She's given me the air.

163
00:14:02,341 --> 00:14:03,399
What?

164
00:14:03,509 --> 00:14:04,737
We had a row.

165
00:14:05,077 --> 00:14:08,604
Oh, I thought she'd given you an heir.

166
00:14:08,881 --> 00:14:10,610
She must be very stupid.

167
00:14:10,716 --> 00:14:12,911
Oh, no, she's brilliant, really.

168
00:14:13,018 --> 00:14:16,454
She speaks German and French
and everything.

169
00:14:16,755 --> 00:14:18,245
Here's her picture.

170
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:21,552
It isn't very good of her, though.

171
00:14:22,528 --> 00:14:24,086
She has her points.

172
00:14:24,964 --> 00:14:28,456
I take it you're smarting
over this air she has given you.

173
00:14:28,901 --> 00:14:31,131
Well, I'm still in love with her.

174
00:14:32,037 --> 00:14:33,800
But she says I'm just a hick.

175
00:14:33,906 --> 00:14:35,635
- A what?
- A farmer.

176
00:14:36,108 --> 00:14:37,803
I've got hay in my hair.

177
00:14:38,711 --> 00:14:40,042
I can't talk on any subject,

178
00:14:40,112 --> 00:14:42,103
- I can't dance, I can't even dress myself.
- Ridiculous.

179
00:14:42,214 --> 00:14:44,205
And I don't know anything
about women's clothes,

180
00:14:44,283 --> 00:14:47,719
and when I have to order dinner
it's always meat, potatoes and pie.

181
00:14:47,786 --> 00:14:51,278
Oh, she says that, does she?
Well, we'll show her she's wrong.

182
00:14:51,390 --> 00:14:53,824
Gosh, John's been in there a long while.

183
00:14:53,926 --> 00:14:56,224
Oh, why didn't we go to a hotel first?

184
00:14:56,295 --> 00:14:57,660
Man, I'm hungry.

185
00:14:58,230 --> 00:15:00,289
Come on, Mac, give him the call.

186
00:15:10,976 --> 00:15:12,273
That's my gang.

187
00:15:12,578 --> 00:15:14,944
- I came over with a band.
- A band of what?

188
00:15:15,014 --> 00:15:17,608
An orchestra.
They're the Wabash Indianians,

189
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:20,652
hired for a job in Paris
and fired through a misunderstanding.

190
00:15:20,719 --> 00:15:24,211
Now they're looking for an engagement.
They're a swell bunch.

191
00:15:27,326 --> 00:15:29,294
They do that rather prettily.

192
00:15:32,531 --> 00:15:34,795
<i>Madame,</i> Scharwenka wants to see you.

193
00:15:34,867 --> 00:15:36,994
She doesn't like her tissue.
She doesn't like the model,

194
00:15:37,102 --> 00:15:39,366
she doesn't like the fit,
and she doesn't like the price.

195
00:15:39,438 --> 00:15:41,736
Oh, you mean she doesn't like it.

196
00:15:41,807 --> 00:15:44,002
Yes, <i>madame,</i> what will you do about it?

197
00:15:44,109 --> 00:15:45,701
Do about it? Let her go.

198
00:15:45,811 --> 00:15:46,869
She'll come back.

199
00:15:46,979 --> 00:15:50,107
She's the rage here right now,
and she's got the best figure in Europe,

200
00:15:50,182 --> 00:15:52,810
but she has to have it dressed,
at least partly.

201
00:15:52,885 --> 00:15:54,876
I'm afraid
she intends to start her screaming.

202
00:15:54,987 --> 00:15:56,545
If she does, stick a pin in her.

203
00:15:56,655 --> 00:15:58,680
Oh, I'd rather use an ice-pick.

204
00:16:01,994 --> 00:16:03,985
This time I left the door open.

205
00:16:12,671 --> 00:16:14,138
Who is she going to stick a pin into?

206
00:16:14,206 --> 00:16:19,166
Scharwenka, a Polish countess who has
spurned the hollow mockeries of society

207
00:16:19,244 --> 00:16:21,735
and gone in for nightclub entertaining.

208
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:26,310
You can see she's talented.

209
00:16:26,385 --> 00:16:28,353
Do you allow her to make such a noise?

210
00:16:28,821 --> 00:16:31,756
- lf she enjoys it, why not?
- Well, suppose the police come in?

211
00:16:31,857 --> 00:16:33,825
Good, they can take her away.

212
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:36,819
But she must be insane
to make such a row.

213
00:16:36,895 --> 00:16:39,090
Stephanie may not be safe with her.

214
00:16:39,264 --> 00:16:42,165
- You feel inclined to stop her?
- Yes, I do.

215
00:16:42,434 --> 00:16:45,096
No, no, no, no, no!

216
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:46,762
You are not the only couturier in Paris!

217
00:16:46,872 --> 00:16:49,500
I am a good advertising
for the house that dresses me!

218
00:16:49,575 --> 00:16:51,702
I do not know why
I come to Roberta anyway!

219
00:16:51,777 --> 00:16:53,870
You... Will you quit pushing me?

220
00:16:54,780 --> 00:16:56,577
I... I beg your pardon.

221
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:08,023
You can't behave like that, you know.

222
00:17:10,896 --> 00:17:14,229
You big beautiful American!

223
00:17:21,807 --> 00:17:23,365
You are very strong.

224
00:17:25,110 --> 00:17:28,568
You do not understand.
These Latin races must be shouted at.

225
00:17:29,748 --> 00:17:32,774
I'm not a Latin
and shouting doesn't impress me.

226
00:17:35,788 --> 00:17:36,846
Hey.

227
00:17:38,157 --> 00:17:40,057
I shall never set foot in this place again.

228
00:17:40,125 --> 00:17:41,990
You do not know
how they have treated me.

229
00:17:42,094 --> 00:17:45,996
This horrible old woman here.
The greedy old <i>diable.</i>

230
00:17:46,098 --> 00:17:47,622
Easy, she's my aunt.

231
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:51,900
Oh, well, I was not blaming it on her.

232
00:17:52,337 --> 00:17:53,998
She is really a genius,

233
00:17:55,074 --> 00:17:58,407
but that little shrew who
runs the business. That Stephanie...

234
00:17:58,477 --> 00:18:00,172
But Stephanie is swell.

235
00:18:00,345 --> 00:18:03,439
What, you are her lover?

236
00:18:03,615 --> 00:18:05,276
I've never seen such a place.

237
00:18:05,350 --> 00:18:08,444
No one thinks of anything
but being somebody's lover.

238
00:18:09,588 --> 00:18:11,852
Well, have you never thought of it?

239
00:18:15,661 --> 00:18:16,923
What happened?

240
00:18:18,263 --> 00:18:20,857
Your nephew has done
most admirably, <i>madame.</i>

241
