474
00:39:01,639 --> 00:39:03,163
You ought to see him, Lord Henry.

475
00:39:03,274 --> 00:39:06,368
Your tailor has surpassed himself.
He looks wonderful.

476
00:39:06,477 --> 00:39:09,139
But then I think
he has the knack of wearing clothes.

477
00:39:09,213 --> 00:39:11,147
Not every man has, you know.

478
00:39:11,449 --> 00:39:14,009
And he has a positive flair for languages.

479
00:39:14,318 --> 00:39:16,980
The way he's taken hold of French
is amazing.

480
00:39:17,054 --> 00:39:20,888
You should have heard him
tell a taxi driver where to go last night.

481
00:39:22,059 --> 00:39:24,493
And Stephanie and I
have given him a few pointers

482
00:39:24,562 --> 00:39:27,292
it would take most men
a lifetime to acquire.

483
00:39:27,798 --> 00:39:29,823
What a start for a young fellow.

484
00:39:30,534 --> 00:39:31,899
<i>Au revoir,</i> my dear.

485
00:39:32,002 --> 00:39:34,971
You never looked lovelier in your life
than you do this minute.

486
00:39:35,039 --> 00:39:36,336
Until tomorrow.

487
00:39:36,407 --> 00:39:39,035
It's always nice to know
I shall see you tomorrow, Henry.

488
00:39:39,143 --> 00:39:41,668
You've been saying
very pleasant things to me, lately, Minnie.

489
00:39:41,746 --> 00:39:44,840
- Not really ill, I hope?
- No.

490
00:39:45,549 --> 00:39:47,244
- Stephanie.
- Lord Henry.

491
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:19,547
- Where is John?
- Taking his French lesson.

492
00:40:19,683 --> 00:40:21,378
Haven't you heard them?

493
00:40:21,752 --> 00:40:22,878
No.

494
00:40:54,752 --> 00:40:56,117
<i>La</i> winner!

495
00:41:22,546 --> 00:41:24,173
Come on, boys, come in.

496
00:41:29,453 --> 00:41:30,943
- So long, prof.
- So long, prof.

497
00:41:39,363 --> 00:41:40,853
Can I get you something?

498
00:41:40,965 --> 00:41:42,193
No, thank you.

499
00:41:42,867 --> 00:41:44,664
Not even a drink of water?

500
00:41:45,569 --> 00:41:46,661
No.

501
00:41:48,339 --> 00:41:49,567
Sing, please.

502
00:42:00,684 --> 00:42:04,586
<i>Yesterday</i>

503
00:42:05,055 --> 00:42:09,151
<i>Yesterday</i>

504
00:42:09,493 --> 00:42:13,156
<i>Days I knew as happy sweet</i>

505
00:42:13,230 --> 00:42:17,667
<i>sequestered days</i>

506
00:42:18,202 --> 00:42:22,104
<i>Olden days</i>

507
00:42:22,339 --> 00:42:26,571
<i>Golden days</i>

508
00:42:26,777 --> 00:42:31,043
<i>Days of mad romance</i>

509
00:42:31,115 --> 00:42:35,108
<i>And love joys</i>

510
00:42:35,219 --> 00:42:40,418
<i>were mine to take</i>

511
00:42:42,059 --> 00:42:45,961
<i>Mine to give</i>

512
00:42:47,031 --> 00:42:50,432
<i>Free and gaily flaming life</i>

513
00:42:50,534 --> 00:42:55,130
<i>was mine to live</i>

514
00:42:55,639 --> 00:43:00,372
<i>Sad am I</i>

515
00:43:00,544 --> 00:43:05,379
<i>Glad am I</i>

516
00:43:05,616 --> 00:43:08,642
<i>for today</i>

517
00:43:08,752 --> 00:43:12,984
<i>I'm dreaming of</i>

518
00:43:13,390 --> 00:43:17,724
<i>yesterday</i>

519
00:43:25,936 --> 00:43:30,100
<i>Joys were mine</i>

520
00:43:30,174 --> 00:43:32,438
<i>to take</i>

521
00:43:33,010 --> 00:43:37,674
<i>mine to give</i>

522
00:43:38,315 --> 00:43:42,308
<i>Free and gaily flaming life</i>

523
00:43:42,419 --> 00:43:47,584
<i>was mine to live</i>

524
00:43:48,025 --> 00:43:52,655
<i>Sad am I</i>

525
00:43:53,097 --> 00:43:57,500
<i>Glad am I</i>

526
00:43:58,135 --> 00:44:01,468
<i>for today</i>

527
00:44:01,538 --> 00:44:04,939
<i>I'm dreaming of</i>

528
00:44:06,810 --> 00:44:11,804
<i>yesterday</i>

529
00:44:35,639 --> 00:44:38,540
- Sophie, Sophie.
- What's the matter?

530
00:44:38,609 --> 00:44:40,201
Here's an article about John.

531
00:44:40,277 --> 00:44:41,471
He's turned dressmaker.

532
00:44:42,312 --> 00:44:43,779
Can you bear it?

533
00:44:44,048 --> 00:44:46,949
lmagine John Kent in a smart dress shop?

534
00:44:47,818 --> 00:44:50,616
He wouldn't know a smart dress
from last year's awning.

535
00:44:50,688 --> 00:44:54,818
Well, the first place I'll make a beeline for
in Paris is going to be Roberta's.

536
00:45:06,870 --> 00:45:08,633
It's all right, Fernande.

537
00:45:13,210 --> 00:45:16,668
I was just saying goodbye to
a room in which I've been very happy.

538
00:45:16,747 --> 00:45:19,841
But you are not
leaving Roberta's, <i>mademoiselle.</i>

539
00:45:23,320 --> 00:45:25,049
Goodbye, Fernande.

540
00:46:03,427 --> 00:46:04,519
<i>Bonjour, Monsieur</i> Fullback.

541
00:46:04,595 --> 00:46:05,789
I wish to place an order.

542
00:46:05,896 --> 00:46:08,558
Would you mind hemstitching
two dozen touchdowns for me?

543
00:46:08,632 --> 00:46:09,724
Oh, lay off.

544
00:46:09,800 --> 00:46:12,462
Would run up for me two field goals
and a bias,

545
00:46:12,569 --> 00:46:14,434
with the score tied in the back?

546
00:46:14,538 --> 00:46:16,062
Kind of a halfback.

547
00:46:17,074 --> 00:46:20,908
I don't get sore often, but I will in a minute
if you two don't shut up.

548
00:46:20,978 --> 00:46:25,074
Do you plan
fitting the ladies yourself, John?

549
00:46:25,482 --> 00:46:28,781
What a picture. Tape measure around
the neck and pin-cushion on the hip.

550
00:46:28,886 --> 00:46:30,080
I ought to spank the two of you.

551
00:46:30,154 --> 00:46:32,054
Now, don't lose
your sense of humor, Johnny.

552
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,818
Why don't you let a guy alone
when he's trying to figure things out?

553
00:46:34,925 --> 00:46:36,790
She just wants to know
what you're going to do.

554
00:46:36,894 --> 00:46:38,794
- That's all.
- I'm going home.

555
00:46:39,062 --> 00:46:42,463
- But you can't. You're Mr. Roberta.
- I'm not. Stephanie is.

556
00:46:42,566 --> 00:46:45,899
I mean, well, Aunt Minnie left no will,
so her property comes to me.

557
00:46:45,969 --> 00:46:48,836
But she always said
the shop was to be Stephanie's.

558
00:46:48,939 --> 00:46:50,736
- Stephanie's going...
- Yes.

559
00:46:55,846 --> 00:46:57,313
We are astonished.

560
00:46:57,481 --> 00:46:58,948
Well, I'm not astonished.

561
00:46:59,016 --> 00:47:01,541
You mean you're going to give
the whole shop to Stephanie?

562
00:47:01,618 --> 00:47:04,849
Yes, right away. That's what Aunt Minnie
wanted and that's what I want.

563
00:47:04,922 --> 00:47:06,719
You're giving it to her without any...

564
00:47:08,826 --> 00:47:09,952
strings?

565
00:47:10,027 --> 00:47:11,790
What do you mean, "strings"?

566
00:47:11,862 --> 00:47:13,796
Oh, she just means

567
00:47:15,599 --> 00:47:16,759
strings.

568
00:47:19,469 --> 00:47:22,734
Well, you make yourselves comfortable.
I've got to find Stephanie.

569
00:47:28,812 --> 00:47:30,507
I was looking for you.

570
00:47:30,981 --> 00:47:32,778
- Well, hello.
- No, no, no.

571
00:47:33,784 --> 00:47:36,719
Can you tell me why no will can be found?

572
00:47:36,820 --> 00:47:39,812
- Well, because there isn't any.
- Why haven't you been able to find it?

573
00:47:39,890 --> 00:47:42,620
- It must have been destroyed.
- So you admit it?

574
00:47:42,860 --> 00:47:44,020
Admit what?

575
00:47:44,561 --> 00:47:47,359
For years Stephanie has worked
to build this business.

576
00:47:47,464 --> 00:47:49,625
It was hers as much as Roberta's.

577
00:47:49,833 --> 00:47:52,028
<i>Madame</i> could not destroy that will.

578
00:47:52,302 --> 00:47:55,328
- Are you trying to say I did?
- I will not say yes or not.

579
00:47:55,405 --> 00:47:58,203
But it looks queer, very queer.

580
00:47:58,408 --> 00:48:00,535
You... Why, you Russian prince!

581
00:48:01,211 --> 00:48:03,179
I'm still boss of this outfit,
and you're fired!

582
00:48:03,247 --> 00:48:06,148
No, no, I am not fired. I am perfectly cool.

583
00:48:06,216 --> 00:48:07,911
I mean you're dismissed.

584
00:48:08,719 --> 00:48:10,744
You think you can get rid of me so easy!

585
00:48:10,854 --> 00:48:13,220
- Get out!
- You think no one will protect Stephanie.

586
00:48:13,323 --> 00:48:16,053
- Stephanie doesn't need your protection.
- While Stephanie stays here

587
00:48:16,159 --> 00:48:18,150
and remains here, I will protect her.

588
00:48:20,030 --> 00:48:23,932
Aren't you ashamed to be quarreling
like two silly little boys?

589
00:48:24,868 --> 00:48:27,393
Please go, Lad, I'll meet you downstairs.

590
00:48:33,010 --> 00:48:34,705
The Russian nobility burns me up anyway.

591
00:48:34,778 --> 00:48:37,076
They're always sticking their noses
in other people's business.

592
00:48:37,180 --> 00:48:39,114
- You don't like the Russian nobility?
- No.

593
00:48:39,216 --> 00:48:40,683
I don't like his hanging around you.

594
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:42,446
I was going to give you the shop anyway.

595
00:48:42,552 --> 00:48:46,181
Oh, you are very magnanimous,
giving me something I don't want.

596
00:48:46,390 --> 00:48:48,085
- You don't want it?
- No.

597
00:48:48,592 --> 00:48:50,082
And who are you to give me gifts?

598
00:48:50,193 --> 00:48:53,287
- Wait a minute, you mustn't act like this.
- I'll act the way I choose.

599
00:48:53,397 --> 00:48:55,194
It's your shop, you run it.

600
00:48:55,265 --> 00:48:56,391
Goodbye.

601
00:48:56,466 --> 00:48:58,457
Hey, wait a minute, Stephanie.

602
00:48:58,635 --> 00:49:01,126
I'm sorry, but I can't be a dressmaker.

603
00:49:01,238 --> 00:49:03,604
I couldn't half carry on the business.

604
00:49:05,642 --> 00:49:08,702
- Maybe you could carry it on half.
- How do you mean?

605
00:49:09,780 --> 00:49:11,611
Well, I mean

606
00:49:13,116 --> 00:49:15,482
- maybe we could be partners.
- No, no.

607
00:49:15,585 --> 00:49:17,246
You like it, you take it, Stephanie.

608
00:49:17,321 --> 00:49:18,913
I've got a football team to coach.

609
00:49:18,989 --> 00:49:22,288
No, I wouldn't accept anything
except in partnership.

610
00:49:22,392 --> 00:49:23,950
Not on your life. That's out.

611
00:49:24,061 --> 00:49:27,155
- All right, then I'm out.
- Oh, wait a minute.

612
00:49:28,265 --> 00:49:30,825
<i>Pardon, mademoiselle,</i>
may I finish this now?

613
00:49:30,934 --> 00:49:32,299
Oh, yes, yes.

614
00:49:33,603 --> 00:49:35,070
Oh, wait a minute.

615
00:49:36,340 --> 00:49:37,466
May she?

616
00:49:38,241 --> 00:49:41,404
I mean, yes. Certainly, my good woman.

617
00:49:45,148 --> 00:49:47,241
You'll make a very nice partner.

618
00:49:47,784 --> 00:49:51,515
It isn't generally known that <i>Madame</i>
has been letting me do all the designing.

619
00:49:51,621 --> 00:49:54,488
So we'll have to startle them
with daring styles.

620
00:49:55,025 --> 00:49:57,357
- Partners.
- Partners.

621
00:49:59,663 --> 00:50:01,858
Oh, John, look. We've had a brainstorm.

622
00:50:01,965 --> 00:50:05,662
Instead of you going home, why don't
you and Stephanie become partners?

623
00:50:10,874 --> 00:50:12,637
Huck, you're brilliant.

624
00:50:12,809 --> 00:50:14,640
What do you say, Stephanie?

625
00:50:15,879 --> 00:50:18,848
No, not on your life. That's out.

626
00:50:19,549 --> 00:50:21,517
You'll make a very nice partner.

627
00:50:21,618 --> 00:50:25,782
It isn't generally known that <i>Madame</i>
has been letting me do the designing.

628
00:50:27,691 --> 00:50:30,524
We'll have to startle them
with daring styles.

629
00:50:32,662 --> 00:50:34,493
- Partners.
- Partners.

630
00:50:35,799 --> 00:50:38,666
Countess, you shall be our first customer.

631
00:50:46,576 --> 00:50:47,804
Yvonne.

632
00:50:49,413 --> 00:50:52,507
This we call <i>le Petit Trianon.</i>

633
00:50:53,216 --> 00:50:55,081
If you don't like any of these,
say so, won't you?

634
00:50:55,185 --> 00:50:57,016
Gee, I think they're swell.

635
00:51:00,690 --> 00:51:03,557
And this is <i>le train bleu.</i>

636
00:51:05,429 --> 00:51:08,262
Oh, that one's a honey.
That's the one I'd take.

637
00:51:10,434 --> 00:51:13,835
Do your ecstasies
refer to the gown or the girl?

638
00:51:14,938 --> 00:51:17,600
Oh, I hadn't noticed the girl,
but now that you mention her,

639
00:51:17,707 --> 00:51:19,174
- I'd take...
- Yes?

640
00:51:19,242 --> 00:51:21,676
The gown. Less upkeep.

641
00:51:24,214 --> 00:51:27,183
This is called <i>la sirene noire.</i>

642
00:51:34,224 --> 00:51:36,454
Does not she look wonderful in that?

643
00:51:37,060 --> 00:51:38,527
Marvelous.

644
00:51:39,029 --> 00:51:40,690
Just like a peeled eel.

645
00:51:47,637 --> 00:51:49,264
I don't like that one.

646
00:51:50,140 --> 00:51:51,266
Liane...

647
00:51:52,776 --> 00:51:53,936
Albert.

648
00:51:54,478 --> 00:51:56,810
Maybe we could do something about it.

649
00:51:58,882 --> 00:52:01,908
Albert, do you suppose
we could raise this back a little?

650
00:52:01,985 --> 00:52:04,613
If you don't mind, I'd like that dress out.

651
00:52:05,455 --> 00:52:07,389
- As bad as that, huh?
- Worse.

652
00:52:08,492 --> 00:52:10,255
All right, then it's out.

653
00:52:10,460 --> 00:52:12,052
Take it away, Albert.

654
00:52:13,964 --> 00:52:16,558
This is <i>le ciel gris.</i>

655
00:52:33,283 --> 00:52:35,342
That is the one I will take.

656
00:52:36,153 --> 00:52:39,680
And tall, handsome gentlemen
with large bank accounts

657
00:52:39,789 --> 00:52:42,314
will be asking for my telephone number.

658
00:52:44,127 --> 00:52:45,526
And getting it.

659
00:52:47,130 --> 00:52:49,655
And won't they be surprised
when I answer?

660
00:52:53,670 --> 00:52:56,434
Well, so long.
Tell the Countess I'll be waiting for her.

661
00:52:56,506 --> 00:52:57,632
Where?

662
00:52:57,841 --> 00:52:59,934
Oh, either on the right side
of the Left Bank,

663
00:53:00,010 --> 00:53:01,705
or the left side of the right bank.

664
00:53:03,180 --> 00:53:06,047
- I think you're swell not to be angry.
- Angry?

665
00:53:07,350 --> 00:53:10,683
I hope we're good enough friends
for you to express an opinion.

666
00:53:10,787 --> 00:53:14,223
And I hope we're good enough friends
for you to dine with me tonight.

667
00:53:14,324 --> 00:53:16,349
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Tomorrow night.

668
00:53:17,060 --> 00:53:18,357
I'm very sorry.

669
00:53:19,196 --> 00:53:22,324
I'll tell you, the night
Huck opens at the Café Russe.

670
00:53:24,134 --> 00:53:25,226
All right.

671
00:53:25,735 --> 00:53:27,362
Gee, that'll be swell.

672
00:53:35,078 --> 00:53:36,170
Yes.

673
00:53:36,246 --> 00:53:38,874
I've always been interested
in newspaper work.

674
00:53:38,982 --> 00:53:40,347
Have you anything more to say?

675
00:53:40,417 --> 00:53:41,850
I think he's said enough.

676
00:53:41,918 --> 00:53:43,317
I haven't any more paper.

677
00:53:43,386 --> 00:53:45,911
Oh, we have reams and reams of it here.

678
00:53:46,156 --> 00:53:47,248
Oh, thanks.

679
00:53:48,091 --> 00:53:50,685
A football player
owning a dress shop is news, isn't it?

680
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:51,852
Good news.

681
00:53:52,362 --> 00:53:54,193
Well, that's what I say,
almost too good to be true,

682
00:53:54,264 --> 00:53:55,788
and that's why
we want you to have it first.

683
00:53:55,865 --> 00:53:59,596
So that you can write it in your own sweet
charming way that you've made famous,

684
00:53:59,703 --> 00:54:00,931
Miss...

685
00:54:01,938 --> 00:54:06,102
We want you to introduce it
in your own inimitable style, Miss...

686
00:54:06,576 --> 00:54:07,838
- Jones.
- Jones.

687
00:54:08,211 --> 00:54:09,371
Jones.

688
00:54:09,446 --> 00:54:12,279
But I'm still sore about all those
silly jokes they're printing about me.

689
00:54:12,382 --> 00:54:13,849
Yes, but they print it.

690
00:54:13,917 --> 00:54:17,045
Every time they make a joke,
a million francs pour in.

691
00:54:17,454 --> 00:54:20,617
It's a pretty expensive joke
on somebody else, I think.

692
00:54:21,124 --> 00:54:24,218
- Now, when Mr. Kent designs clothes...
- When I what?

693
00:54:24,294 --> 00:54:26,524
Does Mr. Kent design clothes, too?

694
00:54:26,763 --> 00:54:29,254
- No.
- Oh, modesty, modesty.

695
00:54:29,899 --> 00:54:34,563
Mr. Kent's idea is to introduce
the football motif into dress designing.

696
00:54:35,138 --> 00:54:38,630
The outdoor flavor will make
the evening clothes look healthier.

697
00:54:38,742 --> 00:54:42,109
Oh, wait till you see our
end-around-end evening creation.

698
00:54:42,245 --> 00:54:44,213
You know, the one
with the dash-off center.

699
00:54:44,281 --> 00:54:46,112
Has Mr. Kent any more ideas?

700
00:54:46,216 --> 00:54:48,150
- No.
- Oh, yes, thousands and thousands.

701
00:54:48,251 --> 00:54:51,550
As a matter of fact, Mr. Kent's
main idea is to design women's dresses

702
00:54:51,621 --> 00:54:53,088
the way men think they should be.

703
00:54:53,156 --> 00:54:54,885
And how do you men
think they should be?

704
00:54:54,958 --> 00:54:56,050
Not so naked.

705
00:54:56,126 --> 00:55:00,392
Well, well, he means that
if clothes are to clothe, they should clothe.

706
00:55:00,630 --> 00:55:04,589
It's more stimulating
to the imagination, if clothes clothe.

707
00:55:05,168 --> 00:55:06,897
That's very unique.

708
00:55:06,970 --> 00:55:08,062
Yes.

709
00:55:08,138 --> 00:55:12,302
And pockets in all dresses,
especially in the evening ones,

710
00:55:12,609 --> 00:55:14,406
so the women can pack their own junk.

711
00:55:14,477 --> 00:55:16,809
The bulging pockets of the male
will disappear forever.

712
00:55:16,913 --> 00:55:19,245
Women will not have to
depend upon their male escorts.

713
00:55:19,316 --> 00:55:20,681
They'll be much more independent.

714
00:55:20,784 --> 00:55:23,309
As a matter of fact... As a matter of fact,

715
00:55:24,154 --> 00:55:27,555
pockets will make
the female more female.

716
00:55:27,657 --> 00:55:28,783
Very nice.

717
00:55:28,858 --> 00:55:31,383
And gloves attached to the dress,

718
00:55:31,494 --> 00:55:32,620
so they won't get lost.

719
00:55:32,696 --> 00:55:35,494
They'll be worn on a jeweled...
Around the neck.

720
00:55:35,565 --> 00:55:36,691
Brilliant!

721
00:55:43,239 --> 00:55:45,799
Well, I really must be going now.

722
00:55:46,176 --> 00:55:47,609
- Oh, that's too bad.
- That's fine.

723
00:55:50,914 --> 00:55:53,883
- Have you had enough?
- Yes, I think I have quite enough.

724
00:55:53,983 --> 00:55:56,884
- Now tell me, what paper will this be in?
- Paper?

725
00:55:57,020 --> 00:55:59,215
Why, I'm Miss Jones. I'm syndicated.

726
00:55:59,322 --> 00:56:02,018
When you talk to me,
you're telling the world.

727
00:56:04,728 --> 00:56:06,161
How was I, toots?

728
00:56:09,032 --> 00:56:10,761
Pardon, <i>monsieur,</i> a lady to see you.

729
00:56:10,867 --> 00:56:13,301
- Another newspaper woman?
- An American, I think.

730
00:56:13,370 --> 00:56:14,667
A Miss Teale.

731
00:56:15,138 --> 00:56:17,072
Sophie! Send her in, please.

732
00:56:17,340 --> 00:56:19,069
Huck, she's here.

733
00:56:19,242 --> 00:56:22,700
That's great, and just when
you were getting along so swell.

734
00:56:23,513 --> 00:56:24,912
You don't appreciate her.

735
00:56:25,014 --> 00:56:27,209
I know she seems
a little hard and sophisticated.

736
00:56:27,317 --> 00:56:29,182
But underneath she's a pearl.

737
00:56:29,252 --> 00:56:30,810
And a pearl, so I am told,

738
00:56:30,887 --> 00:56:33,185
is the result
of a chronic irritation on an oyster.

739
00:56:33,256 --> 00:56:35,156
What do you know
about anything, anyway?

740
00:56:35,225 --> 00:56:38,592
- I know about everything, every way.
- Then you must know Sophie's swell.

741
00:56:38,695 --> 00:56:42,597
John, every day you act worse,
but today you're acting like tomorrow.

742
00:56:45,935 --> 00:56:47,402
- Hello, John.
- Sophie!

743
00:56:47,504 --> 00:56:49,734
You're awfully hard to see
since you became a couturier.

744
00:56:49,839 --> 00:56:51,864
Not for you, Sophie.
When did you arrive in Paris?

745
00:56:51,941 --> 00:56:53,033
This morning.

746
00:56:53,109 --> 00:56:54,599
How long are you going to stay?

747
00:56:54,711 --> 00:56:56,406
Oh, hello, Huckleberry.

748
00:56:56,613 --> 00:56:57,773
Hello, Soph.

749
00:56:58,047 --> 00:57:00,106
Mother and I
are going to Switzerland on Saturday.

750
00:57:00,216 --> 00:57:02,411
Goodbye, John. I'll see you Sunday.

751
00:57:05,422 --> 00:57:07,413
Don't mind him, he's only clowning.

752
00:57:07,524 --> 00:57:08,718
Thank you, dear.

753
00:57:08,792 --> 00:57:12,455
Well, so you're here now.

754
00:57:12,562 --> 00:57:13,620
Yes.

755
00:57:14,230 --> 00:57:17,893
- Aren't you pleased to see me?
- Sophie, I've tried to forget you.

756
00:57:18,268 --> 00:57:19,758
And have you, John?

757
00:57:21,304 --> 00:57:23,772
I thought I had,

758
00:57:24,374 --> 00:57:26,069
but now I know I haven't.

759
00:57:29,279 --> 00:57:30,746
Gee, you're swell.

760
00:57:31,915 --> 00:57:35,043
John, you have a line
that just sweeps a girl right off her feet.

761
00:57:35,118 --> 00:57:36,642
Yeah, sure.

762
00:57:37,320 --> 00:57:39,117
When are you going to show me Paris?

763
00:57:39,222 --> 00:57:42,055
You'd be bored seeing Paris
with a small-town hick like me,

764
00:57:42,125 --> 00:57:44,252
who only knows how to order
meat and potatoes and pie.

765
00:57:44,327 --> 00:57:46,989
Oh, please forget I ever said those things.

766
00:57:47,163 --> 00:57:49,825
I only said them
because you were going away.

767
00:57:50,733 --> 00:57:52,428
I didn't want you to go.

768
00:57:53,336 --> 00:57:56,237
- I loved you so much.
- It was a funny way to love me.

769
00:57:56,306 --> 00:58:00,504
But, John, darling,
don't you ever say things you don't mean?

770
00:58:00,610 --> 00:58:01,668
No.

771
00:58:08,084 --> 00:58:12,350
Well, maybe I do.
Don't cry, Sophie, I don't like it.

772
00:58:14,958 --> 00:58:18,450
I can't help it. I'm so unhappy.

773
00:58:20,296 --> 00:58:22,958
I came all the way to Paris just to see you.

774
00:58:24,801 --> 00:58:28,202
- Only to find you don't love me anymore.
- But I do, Sophie, honest I do.

775
00:58:30,707 --> 00:58:32,038
Oh, John.

776
00:58:37,113 --> 00:58:40,514
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Oh, come in, Stephanie.

777
00:58:41,818 --> 00:58:45,015
May I present Miss Sophie Teale?

778
00:58:45,288 --> 00:58:47,188
My partner Stephanie.

779
00:58:47,857 --> 00:58:49,381
How do you do?

780
00:58:49,826 --> 00:58:52,556
When I come in for a new gown,
may I ask for you?

781
00:58:52,662 --> 00:58:54,493
Oh, that'll be swell.

782
00:58:55,632 --> 00:58:57,566
Well, I'll run along.
I know how busy you are.

783
00:58:57,667 --> 00:59:01,159
- No, I'll see you to the door.
- No. No. Business before pleasure.

784
00:59:01,237 --> 00:59:04,400
But I'll save Wednesday for you.
Lunch and dinner and the evening.

785
00:59:04,507 --> 00:59:06,566
That's fine. It's a date.

786
00:59:08,912 --> 00:59:10,470
Goodbye, miss.

787
00:59:23,826 --> 00:59:27,227
- Stephanie, I want to...
- Why, when you have time,

788
00:59:27,330 --> 00:59:31,699
- I wish you'd look over these materials.
- But I want to tell you about Sophie.

789
00:59:31,935 --> 00:59:35,996
- She's very lovely.
- Yes, that is... I mean she...

790
00:59:38,107 --> 00:59:41,372
Holy smokes,
haven't we a date for next Wednesday?

791
00:59:41,444 --> 00:59:44,607
Oh, have we? I'm sure we haven't.

792
01:00:00,697 --> 01:00:03,029
This we call <i>le lys doré.</i>

793
01:00:08,905 --> 01:00:12,272
If I weren't going out with Johnny,
I wouldn't be so particular.

794
01:00:12,375 --> 01:00:16,072
But I'm sure he'll want me to have
something that expresses my personality.

795
01:00:16,179 --> 01:00:19,376
Suppose we have Johnny come in
and help you select something.

796
01:00:19,449 --> 01:00:22,179
He knows so much more
about your personality than I do.

797
01:00:22,251 --> 01:00:24,719
Oh, no. No, please. I want to surprise him.

798
01:00:24,787 --> 01:00:28,848
You know, he's really just a little boy
in spite of his man-of-the-world exterior.

799
01:00:28,925 --> 01:00:32,691
Yes, I suspected that.
I'll see what else I can get for you.

800
01:00:40,370 --> 01:00:41,735
- Oh, hello, Huck.
- Hello.

801
01:00:41,804 --> 01:00:44,272
If you're looking for Johnny,
he's in conference with his lawyer.

802
01:00:44,374 --> 01:00:45,898
Well, then,
maybe you'll have lunch with me.

803
01:00:45,975 --> 01:00:47,533
- Are you busy?
- Very.

804
01:00:47,610 --> 01:00:51,273
I'm trying to find something to suit
the personality of Miss Sophie Teale.

805
01:00:51,381 --> 01:00:52,939
Then you are busy.

806
01:00:53,082 --> 01:00:54,276
Liane.

807
01:00:55,318 --> 01:00:56,876
Excuse me, won't you?

808
01:00:57,487 --> 01:01:00,081
Liane, that dress was discarded.
Why do you have it on?

809
01:01:00,156 --> 01:01:02,317
Albert wanted to make a new top for it.

810
01:01:02,425 --> 01:01:04,791
Oh, all right. Fine.

811
01:01:06,062 --> 01:01:10,431
- Is Miss Teale's personality in there?
- Yes, right in there.

812
01:01:10,933 --> 01:01:12,958
I'll go and torment her a while.

813
01:01:19,642 --> 01:01:22,076
Is that beautiful.
And just made for you, Soph.

814
01:01:22,145 --> 01:01:25,012
- Oh, hello. Do you really think it suits me?
- Oh, certainly.

815
01:01:25,114 --> 01:01:28,345
A little longer sleeves,
it would make an ideal straitjacket.

816
01:01:28,451 --> 01:01:29,611
Some day, by sheer accident,

817
01:01:29,686 --> 01:01:31,244
you're going to say
something funny, Huck.

818
01:01:31,320 --> 01:01:33,754
Oh, Soph, now don't be like that.

819
01:01:33,823 --> 01:01:35,984
Do you mind if I sit here
and help you pick out a gown?

820
01:01:36,092 --> 01:01:39,357
No, I'm trying to find something
that John will like on me.

821
01:01:39,462 --> 01:01:41,123
Something startling.

822
01:01:41,197 --> 01:01:43,859
John loves to be startled by girls' dresses.

823
01:01:44,834 --> 01:01:47,701
Here is a gown
that might please you, Miss Teale.

824
01:02:01,317 --> 01:02:04,343
This gown has both chic
and good breeding.

825
01:02:04,554 --> 01:02:08,888
I'm more interested in its chic.
I can supply the breeding myself.

826
01:02:13,396 --> 01:02:17,389
I know the dress.
Look, Stephanie, you know that one that...

827
01:02:17,700 --> 01:02:21,659
It sort of begins and then in the...

828
01:02:21,804 --> 01:02:23,135
You know, the black one.

829
01:02:23,206 --> 01:02:26,232
- The black one?
- Yes, the one you put aside.

830
01:02:27,076 --> 01:02:28,566
Oh, no. No, I can't.

831
01:02:28,678 --> 01:02:30,543
Oh, yes, you can, Stephanie.
Show it to Miss Teale.

832
01:02:30,646 --> 01:02:32,705
- I know she'd like it.
- Oh, no, Mr. Kent wouldn't...

833
01:02:32,815 --> 01:02:36,012
I'm quite sure Mr. Kent would want
me to see any model you have.

834
01:02:36,085 --> 01:02:38,645
Please have it shown
as quickly as possible.

835
01:02:38,721 --> 01:02:42,054
That's it, Stephanie, please have it shown
as quickly as possible.

836
01:02:42,158 --> 01:02:44,752
Just because it's been set aside
for a marquise,

837
01:02:44,861 --> 01:02:47,489
doesn't mean that it can't be shown.

838
01:02:49,265 --> 01:02:53,929
Very well. Anna, have Liane model
<i>la sirene noire</i> at once, please.

839
01:02:55,938 --> 01:02:59,339
Oh, thank you, Huck.
Now we're getting someplace.

840
01:03:03,279 --> 01:03:06,271
- She'll probably like that dress.
- She's going to like it.

841
01:03:06,382 --> 01:03:07,940
When John sees her in it, oh boy,

842
01:03:08,050 --> 01:03:10,075
he's gonna make her walk home,
ocean and all.

843
01:03:10,186 --> 01:03:13,519
- No, he won't. He's in love with her.
- He only thinks he is.

844
01:03:18,427 --> 01:03:20,622
If he were, would you mind?

845
01:03:22,865 --> 01:03:25,629
I am minding, Huck. Terribly.

846
01:03:29,772 --> 01:03:31,603
Can't you hurry that model?

847
01:03:32,408 --> 01:03:34,308
Yes. Yes, Miss Teale.

848
01:03:44,153 --> 01:03:47,088
Well, now that's the smartest thing
you've shown me. I like it.

849
01:03:47,156 --> 01:03:50,387
It's been discarded.
It wasn't put aside for anyone.

850
01:03:50,459 --> 01:03:53,428
- Huck was mistaken about that.
- Oh, I see.

851
01:03:53,796 --> 01:03:56,321
Well, I think I'll have it just the same.

852
01:03:57,433 --> 01:03:58,798
What shall I do?

853
01:03:59,335 --> 01:04:01,132
You're doing fine.

854
01:04:01,938 --> 01:04:04,133
- How much is it?
- It's only 1,000 francs.

855
01:04:04,240 --> 01:04:06,003
It's hardly worthy of you.

856
01:04:08,311 --> 01:04:11,838
I'm afraid she's right, Sophie.
You know it may not be so becoming.

857
01:04:12,782 --> 01:04:15,080
You're not a very good saleslady.

858
01:04:18,988 --> 01:04:23,982
Maybe I'm wrong, Miss Teale.
That dress might suit you very well.

859
01:04:26,495 --> 01:04:28,622
This is the bit of international diplomacy

860
01:04:28,698 --> 01:04:32,634
I shall boast about to my grandchildren,
the nasty little demons.

861
01:04:34,770 --> 01:04:36,635
I'll take the dress.
But I want to try it on first.

862
01:04:37,807 --> 01:04:39,934
The more I think of it, the more I am sure

863
01:04:40,009 --> 01:04:43,035
the dress will bring out
something elegantly alluring in you.

864
01:04:43,646 --> 01:04:45,705
Well, I always know the moment
I see a dress

865
01:04:45,815 --> 01:04:47,806
whether it'll be right for me or not.

866
01:05:22,151 --> 01:05:23,584
I'll take this drink and then the food.

867
01:05:23,686 --> 01:05:25,381
- Gee, I'm starved.
- Me, too.

868
01:05:25,488 --> 01:05:28,252
- Hello, hello, hello.
- Oh, hello, Huck.

869
01:05:28,557 --> 01:05:30,184
- Hello, Soph.
- Hello.

870
01:05:30,259 --> 01:05:32,420
Oh, say, Huck,
will you take care of Sophie for a minute?

871
01:05:32,495 --> 01:05:35,020
I want to see about a table.
Pardon me, Sophie.

872
01:05:35,097 --> 01:05:38,396
- Here's a drink waiting for you.
- Oh, thanks, John. Thanks.

873
01:05:48,744 --> 01:05:51,577
- Got the new dress on, Soph?
- Certainly.

874
01:05:53,115 --> 01:05:56,209
You don't know it,
but this is a great moment in my life.

875
01:05:56,285 --> 01:05:58,276
- Oh, thank you, Huck.
- Thank you.

876
01:05:58,387 --> 01:06:00,719
Don't you think
this dress does something for me?

877
01:06:00,790 --> 01:06:03,884
- It'll do something for me.
- Oh, now, Huck.

878
01:06:04,727 --> 01:06:08,959
- A dress like this depends on...
- I know, it depends on that shoulder strap.

879
01:06:09,899 --> 01:06:12,561
Has John seen it yet?

880
01:06:16,405 --> 01:06:19,738
- Afraid he won't like it.
- And why not?

881
01:06:20,309 --> 01:06:22,368
He thinks everything I wear is perfect.

882
01:06:22,445 --> 01:06:24,936
If I ever ask him how he likes a dress,
he just looks at me

883
01:06:25,047 --> 01:06:28,244
with calf-eyes and says,
"Gee, darling, you look swell."

884
01:06:29,251 --> 01:06:31,412
I bet he won't say it about that one.

885
01:06:31,487 --> 01:06:34,581
I'll bet you $100 he says,
"Gee, that looks swell."

886
01:06:34,657 --> 01:06:37,421
- Make it francs, and it's a bet.
- Sold.

887
01:06:46,569 --> 01:06:49,299
Look, John,
we want you to settle a little bet.

888
01:06:49,405 --> 01:06:51,339
Sophie has a very important question
to ask you.

889
01:06:51,440 --> 01:06:53,237
Gee, that's swell.

890
01:07:02,251 --> 01:07:05,152
How do you like it? Isn't it a knockout?

891
01:07:05,287 --> 01:07:08,188
It's the worst-looking thing I ever saw.

892
01:07:08,924 --> 01:07:11,324
Gee, darling, you look terrible.

893
01:07:16,332 --> 01:07:18,527
- Who sold it to you?
- Your partner.

894
01:07:19,101 --> 01:07:22,628
She thought it brought out
something elegantly alluring in me.

895
01:07:24,540 --> 01:07:26,440
Oh, she did, did she?

896
01:07:27,276 --> 01:07:30,643
I'm sorry I said anything, Sophie.
It isn't your fault, you send it back.

897
01:07:30,713 --> 01:07:34,774
I will not send it back.
It's the smartest thing in your shop.

898
01:07:34,850 --> 01:07:37,216
But what do you know
about clothes anyway?

899
01:07:37,319 --> 01:07:39,651
You make yourself ridiculous
by even discussing them.

900
01:07:39,722 --> 01:07:43,317
I knew enough about them
to order that thing out of our line.

901
01:07:43,392 --> 01:07:44,984
Let me tell you something, John Kent,

902
01:07:45,061 --> 01:07:47,291
now that you think you know something
about women's clothes...

903
01:07:47,363 --> 01:07:48,625
- Please.
- Now that you are carrying on

904
01:07:48,697 --> 01:07:49,789
- with your dressmaker.
- Shut up.

905
01:07:49,865 --> 01:07:51,992
I won't shut up. You're in love with her.

906
01:07:52,068 --> 01:07:54,127
I could tell it
the minute she came into your office.

907
01:07:54,203 --> 01:07:55,727
Let's go home.

908
01:07:55,971 --> 01:07:58,906
I'll go home and I'll go home alone.

909
01:08:01,077 --> 01:08:02,635
Suit yourself.

910
01:08:03,579 --> 01:08:06,013
- What? You'd let me?
- Why not?

911
01:08:06,415 --> 01:08:09,748
And now we're getting down to cases,
here's something I want to tell you.

912
01:08:09,852 --> 01:08:11,979
You've bawled me out for the last time.

913
01:08:12,054 --> 01:08:13,817
I've stood for all your knocking
and criticism

914
01:08:13,889 --> 01:08:16,687
because it sounded so cute
coming from such a little snip.

915
01:08:16,759 --> 01:08:18,818
And because I thought I loved you.

916
01:08:18,894 --> 01:08:22,921
- Oh, you thought you loved me?
- Yes, and what a sap you've made of me.

917
01:08:23,666 --> 01:08:26,191
Well, it certainly didn't take much effort.

918
01:08:26,268 --> 01:08:29,328
And don't you ever
come crawling back to me again.

919
01:08:29,705 --> 01:08:32,196
Because I'm through. Through!

920
01:08:35,544 --> 01:08:37,102
Do you hear me?

921
01:08:39,381 --> 01:08:40,439
Do you hear me?

922
01:08:40,516 --> 01:08:42,677
Sure, but I thought you said
you were through.

923
01:08:42,751 --> 01:08:44,946
- Well, I am.
- Well, goodbye!

924
01:08:45,888 --> 01:08:47,185
Goodbye!

925
01:08:51,694 --> 01:08:52,922
Noisy.

926
01:08:54,964 --> 01:08:57,592
- Give me a dozen brandies.
- A dozen?

927
01:08:57,766 --> 01:08:59,427
Yeah, and line them up right here.

928
01:10:22,384 --> 01:10:24,716
Is there anything I can do for you?

929
01:10:27,856 --> 01:10:28,948
No.

930
01:10:29,692 --> 01:10:30,886
<i>Think of what you're losing</i>

931
01:10:30,993 --> 01:10:33,621
<i>by constantly refusing to dance with me</i>

932
01:10:33,729 --> 01:10:36,323
<i>You'd be the idol of France with me</i>

933
01:10:36,398 --> 01:10:40,129
<i>And yet you stand there</i>
<i>and shake your foolish head dramatically</i>

934
01:10:40,202 --> 01:10:42,693
<i>While I wait here so ecstatically</i>

935
01:10:42,805 --> 01:10:45,330
<i>You just look and say emphatically</i>

936
01:10:45,407 --> 01:10:49,901
<i>Not this season</i>
<i>There's a reason</i>

937
01:10:50,346 --> 01:10:52,837
<i>I won't dance</i>
<i>Don't ask me</i>

938
01:10:52,915 --> 01:10:55,179
<i>I won't dance</i>
<i>Don't ask me</i>

939
01:10:55,251 --> 01:10:58,345
<i>I won't dance, madam, with you</i>

940
01:10:59,088 --> 01:11:02,990
<i>My heart won't let my feet</i>
<i>do things they should do</i>

941
01:11:04,927 --> 01:11:07,259
<i>You know what? You're lovely</i>

942
01:11:07,363 --> 01:11:09,763
<i>And so what? I'm lovely</i>

943
01:11:09,865 --> 01:11:12,993
<i>But oh, what you do to me</i>

944
01:11:13,502 --> 01:11:17,495
<i>I'm like an ocean wave</i>
<i>that's bumped on the shore</i>

945
01:11:18,274 --> 01:11:22,074
<i>I feel so absolutely stumped on the floor</i>

946
01:11:23,178 --> 01:11:27,444
<i>Ah, but when you dance</i>
<i>you're charming and you're gentle</i>

947
